+{"type":"message","id":"12c5661c","parentId":"7e0c8f8b","timestamp":"2026-03-24T06:10:51.439Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Plan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Build the Weekly Commit Module v1 — a production micro-frontend (TypeScript/React) with Java 21 modular-monolith backend replacing 15Five for weekly planning. Implements structured weekly commitments with RCDO strategy linkage, chess-layer prioritization, lock/reconcile lifecycle with immutable snapshots, explicit carry-forward with provenance, native tickets with status workflow, manager team dashboard with exception review, conservative explainable AI assistance, rules-based notifications, derived read models for reporting, and comprehensive audit logging. Delivered as a route-level Module Federation remote integrated into the PA host app. Note: The PRD recommends Java 21 (§22) and all checks are npm-based; the monorepo root package.json orchestrates both the TypeScript frontend (Vite/React) and Java backend (Gradle) via shell-out scripts. SQL migrations use Flyway against PostgreSQL.\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 20,\n  \"stepTitles\": [\n    \"1. Monorepo scaffolding and build infrastructure\",\n    \"2. Domain model types, enums, and database schema\",\n    \"3. RCDO hierarchy management API\",\n    \"4. Weekly plan creation and commit CRUD API\",\n    \"5. Lock lifecycle and baseline snapshot API\",\n    \"6. Post-lock scope change and reconciliation API\",\n    \"7. Carry-forward and ticket/work item API\",\n    \"8. Team weekly view, manager review, and permissions API\",\n    \"9. Frontend micro-frontend setup and routing\",\n    \"10. RCDO management UI\",\n    \"11. My Week page with commit list and capacity meter\",\n    \"12. Lock flow and reconcile view UI\",\n    \"13. Team Week dashboard UI\",\n    \"14. Tickets UI and search/filter/history views\",\n    \"15. Notifications backend and frontend panel\",\n    \"16. AI provider abstraction and commit assistance\",\n    \"17. AI risk detection and reconciliation assistance\",\n    \"18. Derived read models and operational reporting\",\n    \"19. Configuration management and admin settings\",\n    \"20. Audit logging, accessibility, and integration polish\"\n  ]\n}\n\nPrevious step 7 (Carry-forward and ticket/work item API) has been completed and approved.\nFiles changed in the previous step:\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/cost.json\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/observations.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/sessions/continuous/relay-a/2026-03-24T04-23-35-130Z_4c4202d2-9023-459a-b908-dfaede19919d.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/sessions/continuous/relay-b/2026-03-24T04-35-30-972Z_471484d6-96e0-4a6b-86fc-b9b081fa294f.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/state.json\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/WeeklyCommitRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/WorkItemRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/WorkItemStatusHistoryRepository.java\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/steps/7\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/carryforward\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ticket\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/carryforward\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/ticket\n\nYour session has context from prior steps. The repository may have changed since your last turn.\nBefore making assumptions about file contents, verify the current state of any files you need to modify.\nDo NOT re-read files that are unrelated to the current step.\n\nStep 8: Team weekly view, manager review, and permissions API\n{\n  \"id\": \"step-8\",\n  \"title\": \"Team weekly view, manager review, and permissions API\",\n  \"description\": \"Implement team view (PRD §13 FR-7, FR-8), manager features (PRD §20), and permissions (PRD §19).\\n\\n**TeamWeeklyViewService:**\\n- `getTeamWeekView(teamId, weekStart)`: aggregates all weekly commits for team members for the selected week. Includes assigned tickets with no linked commit (uncommitted assigned work). Includes unassigned tickets targeted to the week (uncommitted unassigned work). De-duplication: tickets linked to commits must NOT appear in the uncommitted section.\\n- Roll-up by RCDO: aggregate points and commit counts by Rally Cry / DO / Outcome.\\n- Chess distribution: count and points per chess piece for the team.\\n- Compliance summary: lock compliance, reconcile compliance per team member.\\n\\n**ManagerReviewService:**\\n- `getExceptionQueue(teamId, weekStart)`: returns exceptions ordered by severity (King/Queen first, then risk level). Exception types: missed/auto lock, missed reconcile, over-budget plans (points > capacity budget), repeated carry-forward (streak >= 2), post-lock major scope increases (>20% point increase), added/changed King after lock, high scope volatility (>3 scope change events).\\n- `addComment(targetType, targetId, managerId, text)`: plan-level or commit-level comments. Only direct managers may comment on direct reports.\\n- `setCapacityOverride(userId, weekStart, overridePoints, reason)`: manager sets custom capacity budget for a user for a specific week.\\n- `resolveException(exceptionId, resolution)`: mark exception as reviewed/resolved.\\n\\n**Permission/RBAC middleware:**\\n- Role enum: IC, MANAGER, ADMIN.\\n- `AuthorizationService` enforces: IC can only access own plans/commits; Manager can access direct reports' full detail and indirect reports' aggregates; Admin can access all.\\n- Peer visibility: same-team peers see only current and next week basic commit detail (title, owner, priority, chess piece, RCDO, ticket link, state). Hidden: AI risk flags, historical patterns, manager comments, reconcile notes.\\n- Row-level filtering applied at service layer (not just frontend).\\n- Privacy filter on API responses: strip hidden fields based on caller role and relationship.\\n\\n**REST endpoints:**\\n- `GET /api/teams/{id}/week/{weekStart}` — team weekly view\\n- `GET /api/teams/{id}/week/{weekStart}/exceptions` — exception queue\\n- `POST /api/comments` — add comment\\n- `PUT /api/capacity-overrides` — set capacity override\\n- `PUT /api/exceptions/{id}/resolve` — resolve exception\\n\\n**Unit tests:** team view aggregation with de-duplication, RCDO rollup accuracy, exception detection for each type, comment authorization (only direct manager), capacity override application, peer visibility filtering, manager vs IC access boundaries, admin access, privacy field stripping.\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"lint\",\n    \"typecheck\",\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nYou are the first agent to work on this step.\nImplement the changes described above, run checks to verify, and fix any issues before handing off.\nBe thorough — the next agent will review your work and should find it correct.\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/build.gradle.kts: Uses Eclipse JDT formatter instead of google-java-format because google-java-format (and palantirJavaFormat) rely on `com.sun.tools.javac.util.Log$DeferredDiagnosticHandler.getDiagnostics()` which was removed in JDK 25. Future steps should be aware of this constraint; a switch to google-java-format would require either downgrading the JDK to ≤24 or waiting for a google-java-format release that supports JDK 25.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/: Mockito's inline mock maker (InlineBytecodeGenerator) is incompatible with JDK 25. Switched to subclass mock maker via the extensions file. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests — not an issue for our service classes but worth noting for future steps.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/resources/mockito-extensions/org.mockito.plugins.MockMaker: Set to `mock-maker-subclass` to work around Mockito inline-mock-maker incompatibility with JDK 25. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests. Not an issue today, but future steps adding mocks of final types will need to handle this.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency is implemented for repeat calls, but the step also called for optimistic locking or compare-and-swap to protect concurrent runners. I did not see explicit concurrency protection beyond state checks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency relies only on a state check (DRAFT guard). There is no database-level optimistic lock (`@Version`) to protect against concurrent auto-lock runners. This is acceptable for v1 given single-instance deployment, but a future step should add `@Version` to `WeeklyPlan` and a Flyway migration for the `version` column if concurrent scheduling ever becomes a concern.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java: The `getReconciliationView` method allows state RECONCILING or RECONCILED, but `setCommitOutcome` only allows RECONCILING. If a manager views a RECONCILED plan via `getReconciliationView`, then tries to `setCommitOutcome`, they get a 400. This is correct behavior but worth documenting clearly in the API.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java: The `removePostLockCommit` method sets `outcome = CANCELED` immediately (pre-reconciliation). During `submitReconciliation`, this commit is treated as already having an outcome (CANCELED), which is correct. However, calling `setCommitOutcome` on an already-CANCELED (removed) commit during RECONCILING would allow overriding the post-lock cancellation — a guard could prevent this in a future step.\n\nWhen done, explain what you reviewed, what you changed (if anything), and your assessment.\n\nEnd with:\nVerdict: approve  — if the step is complete and correct, no more changes needed\nVerdict: changes_made  — if you made fixes or improvements\nVerdict: replan_needed  — if the step is structurally impossible to complete as planned and needs controller-managed replanning"}],"timestamp":1774332651438}}
